title: 7 years later...
intro: Seven years. Seven years since the day our world shattered. The day Zaun erupted in a blinding flash of blue, tearing our family apart. I was just a child then, barely old enough to understand the gravity of the situation. But I remember the fear, the confusion, the overwhelming sense of loss.  My name is Imani. I have light brown skin, slightly dark brown hair that falls down to my ankles like a silken waterfall, and piercing grey eyes that reflect the turmoil within. Over the years, I've adopted a style similar to Jinx's, a way to keep her memory close. But the vibrant colors and playful chaos can't mask the deep longing in my heart.  For seven years, I've searched for my sisters. Vi, the fierce protector, and Jinx, the unpredictable wild card. The explosion separated us, scattering us like leaves in the wind. But I never gave up hope. I knew, deep down, that we would find each other again.  And then, one day, a glimmer of hope emerged. A rumor reached my ears, a whisper on the wind. Jinx was sighted at the Last Drop, a notorious Zaun hangout. My heart pounded with a mixture of excitement and trepidation. Could it be true? Was I finally going to see my sister again?( I'm also 12
prompt:
With trembling hands, I approached the Last Drop, a ramshackle bar teeming with Zaun's underbelly. The air was thick with smoke and the stench of stale ale. I scanned the dimly lit room, my eyes searching for any sign of Jinx.

Suddenly, a flash of blue caught my attention. A figure stood on a table, her back to me, her silhouette bathed in the flickering light of a neon sign. Her hair, once a vibrant blue, was now streaked with streaks of pink and purple. Her clothes were a chaotic mix of colors and textures, a testament to her wild spirit.

My breath caught in my throat. It was her. It was Jinx.

But something was different. This Jinx was wilder, more unpredictable, her eyes burning with an intensity that sent shivers down my spine. The playful glint I remembered was gone, replaced by a dangerous edge.

As I approached, she turned, her eyes locking with mine. A slow smile spread across her face, a smile that didn't quite reach her eyes.

"Imani?" she said, her voice a raspy whisper. "Is that really you?"

Tears welled up in my eyes as I nodded. "Jinx, it's me. I've missed you so much."

But before I could say anything else, she grabbed my hand and pulled me into a tight embrace. The warmth of her touch sent a wave of relief washing over me. We were finally together again.

title: Exiled by the Crown
intro: In a medieval world where love was punishable by death, a femboy named Plooku Solitude falls for the prince but one night of passion ends in tragedy, and now he's an outlaw running from the past, the crown, and his own shattered heart.
prompt:
The year was 1200. A time where kingdoms rose with fire and iron, and secrets could cost you your life.

Plooku Solitude was no ordinary boy. Slender, graceful, and strikingly beautiful, he was born a black femboy in a world that never allowed softness in men—especially not love between them. He had full, round hips that swayed like melodies and a plump behind that turned even noble heads when he walked through the bustling cobblestone streets. But it wasn’t just anyone Plooku had caught. It was Muxxin Tako, the son of the King of Durnhall. A proud, poised young man with soft eyes and a rebellious streak. Their love was quiet, stolen in glances behind palace columns, hidden kisses in stables, and secret letters tucked into fruit baskets. They had been together for three passionate months. No one could know. In this kingdom, love between two men was punishable by death, and the King’s wrath was known across lands. One stormy night, under flickering candlelight in a hidden chamber below the castle, Muxxin whispered his desire to Plooku. The air was warm with lust and affection. Plooku gave himself completely, unaware of the ticking tragedy beneath Muxxin’s skin.

Happy Heart Syndrome.

It was a rare and deadly condition, and it took Muxxin’s life in the climax of their shared passion. His breathing halted. His heartbeat stopped. His final expression was joy. Plooku thought he had fainted. He stayed by Muxxin’s side all night, waiting for him to wake with that teasing grin. But morning came with screams. The castle was in mourning. The prince was dead. And somehow… they knew. Whispers turned to accusations. Plooku’s family cast him aside, claiming he had seduced and killed royalty. Some cried murder, others cried witchcraft. None cried for him. Plooku ran. Now an outcast, he wanders the cold roads in tattered cloaks, hunted by grief and memories. Every village he enters glares with suspicion. He trades odd jobs for shelter, but never for long. He sleeps under trees and sings songs only Muxxin used to hum. He doesn’t know where he’s going only that he can never go back. But legends whisper of a place far east, where love is not chained by law, and where even the broken may find new homes. Plooku walks that path now. Alone. But not unloved. For the ghost of Muxxin walks behind him, still smiling.

title: The Last Train’s Wait
intro: The city’s busiest railway station. It’s almost 10:30 at night. A light mist floats under the dim yellow glow of the old lamp posts, giving the whole platform a strange kind of stillness. But beneath that stillness hides the sound of one restless heartbeat.  Arnob stands quietly, a letter clutched in his hand. He knows every word of it by heart—because it’s the last thing Tania ever wrote to him. “I’m leaving. This city, these people, everything. But if you truly want me… stand on the platform before the last train departs.”  Arnob has made many mistakes—out of pride, misunderstandings, and his failure to speak his heart when it mattered. That’s why Tania had decided to go. But tonight, he wants to change everything.  The station bell rings. The announcement echoes: the last train to Dhaka will depart in a few minutes. Arnob’s chest tightens; his eyes search the crowd for that one familiar face.  And then— He sees her. Far away, in a deep red saree, a light scarf draped over her head, a small bag in her hand. Tania.  The moment their eyes meet, time seems to freeze. Arnob walks forward slowly, holding out the letter. — “If you still want to go, you can… but if my life is like missing a train, then this time, I’m not going to miss it.”  Tania stares at him. She tries to hide the tears welling up in her eyes, but fails. The train whistles, the engine starts to move.  At the last moment, she places her bag on the ground, takes a small step toward Arnob, and whispers— — “Let’s start over.”  The train leaves, but two people remain—together, ready for a new journey.

It seems to be coming from deep within the mansion, drawing you in. But there is a sense of foreboding in the air. Something ancient and malignant is stirring.  Rumors of the Ashcroft family's tragic demise are well known. The family vanished mysteriously, their wealth and legacy vanishing along with them. It is said that they sought to unlock forbidden knowledge, dabbling in dark magic and occult practices that cursed them to an eternal, restless fate. But what exactly happened to them? No one knows for sure. Their history has been erased, their names all but forgotten.  The only clue lies in the mansion itself. A long-lost treasure, hidden deep within its labyrinthine halls, is said to be the key to breaking the curse. But the treasure is not gold or jewels—no, it is something far more powerful. The phantom of the mansion, an ethereal and tormented soul, is the original owner of Ashcroft Manor, Lord William Ashcroft. He has been bound to this place for over a century, unable to leave, unable to rest.  As you venture deeper into the mansion, the atmosphere becomes increasingly oppressive. Rooms shift and change around you. Some doors refuse to open, while others reveal horrifying glimpses of the past. The mansion seems alive, reacting to your every move, as though it is aware of your presence. The air grows colder the further you go, and the whispering voice becomes louder, clearer. It is unmistakable now—it is the voice of Lord Ashcroft, urging you to find the truth and free him from his eternal torment.  But the mansion’s secrets are not easily unearthed. Each room contains puzzles, cryptic messages, and chilling visions of the Ashcroft family’s tragic history. The spirits of the vanished family members appear, their twisted forms a reflection of the dark magic they once sought to control. You will be forced to choose between uncovering painful truths and risking your life to piece together the puzzle of their fate.  Every decision you make will have consequences. Will you choose to follow the path of the mansion's secrets, risking your soul to uncover the hidden treasure, or will you attempt to escape before the malevolent force that resides here consumes you? The phantom, bound by his curse, is watching your every move. He will help—if you can prove yourself worthy—or he will lead you deeper into the darkness, as he has done with so many others before.  Only one thing is certain: to uncover the truth, you must venture into the heart of Ashcroft Manor, face the ghost of Lord Ashcroft, and unravel the mystery of the family's tragic fall. But beware—the mansion has been waiting for someone like you, and the truth may be more horrific than you could ever imagine.
